{{Infobox political party | name = Hospital to Alta | logo = Logo - Sykehus til Alta.jpg | logo_size = 200px | colorcode = <!-- HTML color code (e.g. red, #FF0000 or Party metadata color template) or transparent for no coloring --> | leader = [[Raymond Londal]] | foundation = <!-- {{Start date|2013|MM|DD}} --> | ideology = [[Single-issue politics|Single-issue]] | headquarters = [[Alta, Norway|Alta]] | international = | website = [https://www.facebook.com/pages/Sykehus-til-Alta/168616535698 Facebook page] | country = Norway | dissolved = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |seats1_title = [[Parliament of Norway|Parliament]] |seats1 = {{Composition bar|0|169}} }}
'''Hospital to Alta''' ({{lang-no|Sykehus til Alta}}) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[political party]] which was active for the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 2013|2013 parliamentary election]]. The party's sole issue was the desire to relocate [[Hammerfest Hospital]], the sole [[hospital]] in western [[Finnmark]], from [[Hammerfest]] to [[Alta, Norway|Alta]]. The party was based on a [[Facebook]] group which gradually developed into a party list for the election. Former [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]] local politician [[Raymond Londal]] was the top candidate, along with nine other people. The party ran exclusively in the constituency of Finnmark. The party received 467 votes, of which 370 were cast in Alta, or 1.2 percent in Finnmark and 3.9 percent in Alta, failing to claim a seat in [[Parliament of Norway|Parliament]]. The party was abolished after the election.
==History== The party had its origins as a Facebook group which has the same name as the party. The issue of starting a party had been discussed at several meetings in relation to the group, although a majority had been opposed to starting a party. On 18 January 2013 the page's main administrator, Raymond Londal, asked for 500 people to like they post if they wanted him to start the preparation for a party, including collecting the necessary 500 signatures needed to register a party. Londal had initially given a deadline to 1 March, but it took only 75 minutes before he had sufficient likes to proceed.<ref name=kosowski>{{cite news |url=http://www.nordlys.no/nyheter/article6451039.ece |title=Sykehus til Alta får egen stortingsliste |date=18 January 2013 |work=[[Nordlys]] |last=Kosowski |first=Alexandra |language=Norwegian |accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref>
Londal started early that he hoped that the list could act as a unified list for several profiled politicians, including the [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party's]] parliamentarian [[Jan-Henrik Fredriksen]] and the [[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal Party's]] [[Trine Noodt]], although these never joined.<ref name=kosowski /> Londal, himself a Conservative Party member of Alta Municipal Council, resigned his membership in the Conservatives to be top candidate for the new list. He continued to meet in the municipal council as a [[independent (politician)|independent]].<ref name=venstre>{{cite news |url=http://www.nrk.no/nordnytt/londal-over-til-venstre-1.11242858 |title=Londal over til Venstre |date=15 September 2013 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] |language=Norwegian |accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref>
Prior to the election Londal stated that he hoped that the list would be able to secure a single candidate to parliament, although he admitted that this was optimistic.<ref name=altapostenprofile /> The party rallied at the school election at [[Alta Upper Secondary School]], claiming 88 of 754 votes, or 12.2 percent, and making them the third-largest party.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.altaposten.no/lokalt/nyheter/Valg/article8216145.ece |title=Sykehuslista tredje størst |last=Reginiussen |first=Arne |date=4 September 2013 |work=[[Altaposten]] |language=Norwegian |accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref> Londal stated the day after the election that the party's function now had been completed and that it would be dissolved. A week later he joined the Liberal Party.<ref name=venstre />
==Issue== [[File:Raymond Londal.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Raymond Londal]], the party's top candidate]]
The party only had a [[Single-issue politics|single issue]], namely that the sole hospital serving western Finnmark should be relocated from Hammerfest to Alta. The party stated that Alta is more centrally located than Hammerfest and argued that a hospital in Alta would give a closer service to the residents, lower transport costs and better quality. Hospital to Alta was opposed to a three-hospital solution for Finnmark, whereby there would be hospitals in both Alta and Hammerfest.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nrk.no/nordnytt/valgportrett_-raymond-londal-1.11193656 |title=Valgportrett: Raymond Londal (Sykehus til Alta) |date=21 August 2013 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] |language=Norwegian |accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref> The issue was especially relevant because there were plans to build a new hospital for the region. Londal mentioned Altagård as a potential location and proposed 2016 as the year for construction to start.<ref name=altapostenprofile>{{cite news |url=http://www.altaposten.no/lokalt/nyheter/Valg/article8184025.ece |title=Partipresentasjon Sykehus til Alta |date=28 August 2013 |work=[[Altaposten]] |language=Norwegian |accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref>
==Election== {{main|Norwegian parliamentary election, 2013}}
Hospital to Alta exclusively ran in the constituency of Finnmark, which is awarded five members of Parliament, including one leveling seat. It was one of fifteen parties to run in the county and the only to run exclusively in Finnmark.<ref name=approval>{{cite news |url=http://www.regjeringen.no/pages/38359959/finnmark.pdf |title=Stortingsvalget 2013 Finnmark Finnmárku |publisher=[[Government.no]] |format=PDF |page=14 |language=Norwegian |accessdate=31 October 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103020011/http://www.regjeringen.no/pages/38359959/finnmark.pdf |archivedate=3 November 2013 |df= }}</ref> The top candidate was the fifty-year-old Raymond Londal, a teacher and municipal council member from Alta. The second candidate was the thirty-seven-year-old May Ragnhild Vasara Jørgensen from Alta and in third place the twenty-four-year-old Erika Niittyvuopio from [[Karasjok]].<ref name=altapostenprofile /> The remainder of the ten candidates were all from Alta.<ref name=approval />
For Finnmark as a whole the party achieved 467 votes, or 1.2 percent, making it the tenth-largest party.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.valgresultat.no/bs4_20.html |title=Resultater for Finnmark Finnmárku |publisher=[[Government.no]] |language=Norwegian |accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref> The party received 370 votes in Alta, or 3.9, making it the sixth-largest party.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.valgresultat.no/bs2_20_12.html |title=Resultater for Alta i Finnmark Finnmárku |publisher=[[Government.no]] |language=Norwegian |accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref> The best result was reached in [[Kautokeino]], where the party received 74 votes, or 5.1 percent, making it the seventh-largest party.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.valgresultat.no/bs2_20_11.html |title=Resultater for Guovdageaidnu Kautokeino i Finnmark Finnmárku |publisher=[[Government.no]] |language=Norwegian |accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref> In Hammerfest the party received one vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.valgresultat.no/bs2_20_4.html |title=Resultater for Hammerfest i Finnmark Finnmárku |publisher=[[Government.no]] |language=Norwegian |accessdate=31 October 2013}}</ref> In the remainder of the municipalities it received a combined 27 votes, with between zero and two per municipality.
