The '''Waterloo Ceremony''' is an annual event in which the [[Duke of Wellington (title)|Duke of Wellington]] pays a symbolic rent for his residence to the reigning Monarch.  The ceremony takes place at [[Windsor Castle]] each year on the 18th of June.

==History==
[[Stratfield Saye House]] in Hampshire was bought by the people of the UK for the first Duke of Wellington; a gift for winning the [[Battle of Waterloo]].

Every year, the current [[Duke of Wellington (title)|Duke of Wellington]] pays the symbolic rent to the reigning Monarch in the form of a flag.

==The Ceremony==
A silk French tricolour, with gold embroidery, and imprinted with the year of presentation upon it, is handed to [[Elizabeth II|HM The Queen]] by the Duke on the anniversary of the victory of the battle, while the Queen is at Windsor.  Therefore, a new flag is produced each year.

Once the Queen is presented with the flag, it is taken by the [[Master of the Household|Castle Superintendent]], to the Guard Chamber, and is placed above a bust of the [[first Duke of Wellington]].

